---
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import HeaderFull from '../components/HamburgerHeader.astro';
import { SEO } from "astro-seo";
import "../styles/global.css"
---

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1, shrink-to-fit=no">
	<head>
         <SEO
      title="Amanda Liczner - About Me"
      description="Amanda Liczner is a researcher of conservation, restoration, and all things bumble bees."
      openGraph={{
        basic: {
          title: "Amanda Liczner - About Me",
          type: "website",
          image: "/AmandaLiczner.jpg",
        }
      }}/>
		<style> 
            body {
            background-image: url("/pictures/rose-petals.png");
            background-color: rgba(0,0,0,.4);
            background-blend-mode: multiply;
            color: #f7f3ed; 
        }
        .page-title {
            font-family: Century Gothic;
            color: #f7f3ed;
        }

        .bee-list {
  list-style-type: none;
  padding-left: 20px;
}

.bee-list li::before {
    content: "";
  display: inline-block;
  width: 20px; 
  height: 20px;
  background-image: url('./bumblebee2.png'); 
  background-size: contain;
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  margin-right: 10px;
}

             </style>
            </head>
        
        <main>
            <HeaderFull />
            <h1 class="page-title  py-12 md:px-12 mx-auto px-2 text-5xl md:text-6xl"> About me </h1>
                <div class="max-w-md mx-auto overflow-hidden md:max-w-4xl my-4 md:text-xl small-screen-padding all-content">
                    <div class="md:flex my-4 md:space-x-4">
                    <div class="md:w-3/5 bee-list">
                        I am a postdoctoral research fellow at the University of Guelph supervised by <a class="hyperlinks" href="https://1in3mouthfuls.org/"> Dr. Nigel Raine. </a> We are testing for possible impacts of pesticides on the movement of bumble bees. We are doing this with the help of tiny radio tags that track their movement! Check out my current work page for more details!
                        <br>
                        <br>
                        My research interests are:
                        <ul>
                        <li> behavioural ecology</li>
                        <li> conservation</li>
                        <li> restoration </li>
                        <li> pollinators </li>
                        <li> all things bumble bees!</li>
                    </ul> 
                </div>
                <div class="md:w-2/5 my-4">
                    <img class="h-72 w-full object-cover md:h-full" src="/AmandaLiczner.jpg" alt="Amanda Liczner headshot in the field">
                </div>
                </div>
                <div class="md:flex my-4 md:space-x-4">
                    <div class="md:w-2/5 my-4">
                      <img class="h-72 w-full object-cover md:h-full" src="/Bumble.jpg" alt="Bumble bee with a radio tag on dandelions">
                      </div>
                      <div class="md:w-3/5 bee-list">
                        I have studied bumble bees using a variety of methods: 
                        <ul> 
                        <li> field sampling of bees, nests, and plants </li>
                        <li> statistical modelling  </li>
                        <li> conservation planning </li>
                        <li> systematic literature reviews </li> 
                        <li> radio telemetry to study movement behaviour </li> 
                        <br>
                        </ul> You can learn more about the skills I have picked up along the way on my skills page.
                        <br>
                        <br>
                        Why so much focus on bumble bees? BEE-cause they are the best! They can be found across many continents, are great pollinators for wild and crop plants, and have a very interesting life history. 
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="my-12">
                 
                        Although my specialty is bumble bee I am open to working on any ecological research project, especially those with an applied angle (see some of my past research examples on my experience page). 
                        <br>
                        <br>
                        <div class="text-center"> If you are looking to collaborate take a look at my contact page!
                            <br>
                            <br>
                            <a href ="/aboutme" class = "bg-transparent hover:bg-lime-700 text-gray-100  font-semibold hover:text-white py-2 px-4 border border-slate-200 hover:border-transparent rounded">
                                Contact
                            </a>
                        </div>
                </div>
                <div class="md:flex my-4 md:space-x-4">
                    <div class="md:w-2/4 my-4">
                    <img class="h-54 w-full object-cover md:h-full" src="/Phoebe.jpg" alt="Amanda Liczner with Phoebe in a kayak">
                    </div>  
                    <div class="md:w-2/4 my-4">
                        When I am not out searching for bumble bees or analyzing data, you can find me hanging out with my dog, gardening, hiking, playing violin, baking or crafting! </div>
              </div>
            </div>
        </main>
		<Footer />

</html>
